ges/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=3D"27" alt=3D"D=
OWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download <span class=3D"display-i displ=
ay-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</span></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
In general, a tetrahedron is a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Pol=
yhedron.html">polyhedron</a> with four
sides.
</p>
<p>
If all faces are congruent, the tetrahedron is known as an <a href=3D"https=
://mathworld.wolfram.com/IsoscelesTetrahedron.html">isosceles tetrahedron</=
a>. If all faces are congruent to an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.c=
om/EquilateralTriangle.html">equilateral
 triangle</a>, then the tetrahedron is known as a <a href=3D"https://mathwo=
rld.wolfram.com/RegularTetrahedron.html">regular
 tetrahedron</a> (although the term "tetrahedron" without further qualifica=
tion
 is often used to mean "<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/RegularTet=
rahedron.html">regular tetrahedron</a>").
 A tetrahedron having a trihedron all of the face angles of which are right=
 angles
 is known as a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/TrirectangularTetra=
hedron.html">trirectangular tetrahedron</a>.
</p>
<p>
A general (not necessarily regular) tetrahedron, defined as a convex <a hre=
f=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Polyhedron.html">polyhedron</a> consisti=
ng of four (not necessarily identical) <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/Triangle.html">triangular</a>
 faces can be specified by its <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Pol=
yhedronVertex.html">polyhedron vertices</a>
 as <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Tetrahedron/=
Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100=
%" border=3D"0" width=3D"71" height=3D"22" alt=3D"(x_i,y_i,z_i)">, where <i=
mg src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Tetrahedron/Inline=
2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bor=
der=3D"0" width=3D"35" height=3D"21" alt=3D"i=3D1">, ..., 4. Then the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Volume.html">volume</a> of the
 tetrahedron is given by
</p>
<div>
<table summary=3D"" width=3D"100%" align=3D"center" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
