</p>
<p>
There are a number of interesting and unexpected theorems on the properties=
 of general (i.e., not necessarily regular) tetrahedron (Altshiller-Court 1=
979). If a plane divides
 two opposite edges of a tetrahedron in a given ratio, then it divides the =
volume
 of the tetrahedron in the same ratio (Altshiller-Court 1979, p.&nbsp;89). =
It follows
 that any plane passing through a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/=
Bimedian.html">bimedian</a> of a tetrahedron
 bisects the volume of the tetrahedron (Altshiller-Court 1979, p.&nbsp;90).
</p>
<p>
